USE CASE DIAGRAM
What is this diagram?
This Use Case Diagram represents how different users interact with the SCHOLARITY system. It shows the main actors and the actions they can perform within the system boundary.

Actors:

STUDENT
The student is the primary user of the system. Students can:
Login/Register
Select Academic Program
View educational resources
Download past papers or notes
Access lecture videos
Book appointment with tutor
Submit queries

The login/register function includes:
Create login
Delete login
Update login

Lecture videos include:
Watch lecture
Download lecture

Query includes:
Submit query

TEACHER
The teacher supports the system by:
Uploading resources
Resolving student queries

ADMIN
The admin manages the system by:
Manage system
Resolve queries

System Boundary:
All use cases are inside the system boundary which represents the SCHOLARITY platform. The actors are outside the boundary and interact with the system.

Relationships:
The diagram uses <<include>> to represent mandatory functions within login operations.
It uses <<extend>> to represent optional or additional features such as watching lectures and resolving queries.

Purpose of the Diagram:
The purpose of this diagram is to clearly define the functional requirements of the system and show how each actor interacts with SCHOLARITY. It ensures that all required system functionalities are identified before development.


CLASS DIAGRAM
What is this diagram?
The Class Diagram represents the structural design of the SCHOLARITY system. It illustrates the main classes of the system, their attributes, methods, and the relationships between them. This diagram helps in understanding how different components of the system interact with each other.

Main Classes:

USER
The User class is the parent class of the system. It contains common attributes and functions shared by all users of the platform.

Attributes:
userID
username
password

Methods:
login()
logout()

STUDENT
The Student class inherits from the User class. It represents students who use the platform to access educational materials and academic support.

Attribute:
academicProgram

Methods:
selectProgram()
viewResources()
downloadFiles()
watchLecture()
submitQuery()

TEACHER
The Teacher class also inherits from the User class. Teachers are responsible for uploading educational materials and assisting students.

Attribute:
department

Methods:
uploadResources()
uploadLecture()
manageAppointments()

ADMIN
The Admin class inherits from the User class and represents the system administrator who manages the overall platform.

Attribute:
adminLevel

Methods:
manageSystem()
resolveQuery()
manageUserLogins()

RESOURCE
The Resource class represents educational materials available in the system.

Attributes:
resourceID
title
category
fileType

Method:
updateDetails()

APPOINTMENT
The Appointment class represents booking sessions between students and tutors.

Attributes:
appointmentID
dateTime
status

Methods:
confirmBooking()
cancelBooking()

QUERY
The Query class represents questions submitted by students.

Attributes:
queryID
message
status

Method:
updateStatus()


Relationships:
The STUDENT, TEACHER, and ADMIN classes inherit from the USER class, demonstrating inheritance in the system.
Teachers upload resources that are stored in the RESOURCE class.
Students can view and download resources uploaded by teachers.
Students can book appointments which are managed through the APPOINTMENT class.
Students submit queries through the QUERY class and these queries can be resolved by the Admin.

Purpose of the Diagram:
The purpose of the class diagram is to define the structure of the SCHOLARITY system and demonstrate how different classes interact. It helps developers understand system organization before implementation.


WIREFRAMES
What are these Wireframes?
These wireframes represent the structural layout of the SCHOLARITY web platform. They illustrate how different components of the interface are arranged before the final  visual design is applied. The wireframes focus on the placement of navigation menus, buttons, content sections, and user interaction elements to ensure a logical and user-friendly structure for the system.

Home Page:
The home page wireframe shows the main interface students see after logging into the system.

This page includes:
- A navigation bar containing the SCHOLARITY logo and main menu options such as Home, Resources, Tutors, and Video Lectures.
- A welcome section that greets the user and provides a brief introduction to the platform.
- Action buttons such as "Explore Resources" and "Find a Tutor" which allow users to quickly access the main features of the platform.
- Information cards displaying user activity such as number of downloads, tutoring sessions booked, videos watched, and saved bookmarks.
- Notification and upcoming session sections that keep students updated about important activities.

Resources Page:
The resources page wireframe illustrates how educational resources are organized and displayed within the system.

This page includes:
- The main navigation bar for consistent system navigation.
- A grid layout that displays multiple educational resources in card format.
- Each resource card contains the resource title, short description, subject tags, file type indicators, and file details.
- A download button that allows students to easily access the selected resource.

Tutors Page:
The tutors page wireframe demonstrates how tutor profiles are presented to students.

This page includes:
- Tutor profile cards displayed in a structured grid layout.
- Each tutor card includes a profile picture, tutor name, rating, and number of reviews.
- Subject expertise tags showing the tutor’s specialization.
- Pricing information indicating the hourly tutoring rate.
- A "Book Session" button allowing students to schedule tutoring sessions.

Video Lectures Page:
The video lectures wireframe shows how recorded educational videos are organized and presented within the SCHOLARITY platform.

This page includes:
- A search bar that allows students to search for videos or instructors.
- Filter options such as subject and education level to help students find relevant video lectures.
- A grid layout displaying multiple video lecture cards.

Each video card contains:
- A video thumbnail preview.
- The lecture title and brief description.
- Instructor information.
- Subject tags and curriculum level.
- The number of views and video duration.


